<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>The significance of Richard Whitney's stock market intervention was:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Successfully preventing the crash</option>
            <option letter="b">Failing to restore market confidence</option>
            <option letter="c">Implementing new regulations</option>
            <option letter="d">Stabilizing bank assets</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Richard Whitney's dramatic intervention on October 24, 1929 ("Black Thursday"), when he purchased large blocks of U.S. Steel shares above market price, failed to restore market confidence. Despite this visible attempt to halt the panic, the stock market crash continued through "Black Tuesday," showing the limitations of private efforts to stabilize the market during the crisis.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
